Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 9. Boil a full #kettle{}.

Meanwhile, peel and chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm chunks. Peel the 
@garlic cloves{2}.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. 
Add the potatoes and garlic cloves to the water and cook until just tender, 
~{12-14%minutes}.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%grams}.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine the @red wine vinegar{12%ml}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and 
@olive oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Add the tomatoes, toss to coat, then set aside.

When the potatoes have 1 min remaining, add the @peas{120%grams} to the same 
pan. Cook for the remaining time, then drain in a #colander{} and allow to 
steam, uncovered, for ~{2%minutes}.

Return to the pan, off the heat. Add the @korma curry paste{50%grams}, 
@butter{10%grams} and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Season with pepper.

Mash the potatoes and peas with a #potato masher{}, ensuring the mixture isn't 
too smooth so that some chunks of potato remain. Stir in the 
@breadcrumbs{50%grams} and half the coriander.

Allow the potato mixture to cool slightly, then shape into 2cm thick patties, 3 
per person. Transfer the cakes to a large, lightly oiled #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @olive oil{}, then bake on the top shelf of your oven until 
golden, ~{24-26%minutes}. Carefully turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%grams} 
and remaining coriander. Season with salt.

When everything's ready, add the @baby leaf mix{50%grams} to the tomato bowl and 
toss to coat.

> TIP: Don't add the leaves too early or they'll go soggy.

Share the pea and potato cakes between your plates. Drizzle over the 
@mango chutney{40%grams}.

Serve the tomato salad and coriander yoghurt alongside. Enjoy!